 Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Paveley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Pawley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pavelin","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Paveley   (  see  Pawley  ) with an excrescent  <i>-n</i>."]},{"name":"Pawley","meanings":["English: variant of   Pauley  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":58,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":67,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Paveley VI was born about 1270, in Paulerspury, Northamptonshire, England, his father, Lawrence de Paveley of Paulerspury, was 27 and his mother, Mrs. Sarra De Paveley, was 32. He married Elizabeth Shampevelk about 1295, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 14 November 1346, in his hometown, at the age of 77."},"et":{"about 1270–14 November 1346":"umbes 1270–14. november 1346","1270–1346":"1270–1346","1275–1346":"1275–1346","1296–1391":"1296–1391","1334–1392":"1334–1392","1245–1329":"1245–1329","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1392":"1392","1391":"1391","1270":"1270","14 November 1346":"14. november 1346","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1346":"1346","1334":"1334","after 1329":"pärast 1329","1245":"1245","1453":"1453","about 1295":"umbes 1295","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Paulersbury, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"